¹⁵ Imnzealiatam. The word ἅμεσος is used in two senses by Aristotle. l. For a proposition not proved by any hiphar middle term; i. e. an axiomatic principle, forming the first premise of a demonstration. Such is the sense in Anal. Post. i. 2. 2. and ii. 19. l. 2. For a premise immediate as regards its conclusion; i. e. not requiring the insertion of lower middle terms to connect its terms with those os the conclusion. Such is the sense in An. Post. i. 13. 1. This second sense is intended here.

Of an immediate proposition in the first sense, the favourite scholastie example was, Omna animal rationale eet risibilm the predicate being regarded as flowing directly from the subject, not as connected with it by any intervening cause. Whereas in hama est risibile, between predicate and subject intervenes the middle term rationalia. See Aquinas, Opusc. 48. de Syll. Demon. chap. 5. Zabarella, in I. Anal. Post. c. 2. cont. 9. Hence the following specimen os a dentonetratio potissima:

Orare animal rationale est risibile ; Omnis lamo eet animal rationale; ergo Omnis homo est risibilia.
